    id: "f-rmc2-02",
    title: "Whales off the Port Side",
    text: "My uncle Dan has worked on the ferry between the mainland and the islands for almost twenty years, and every summer he invites one of his nieces or nephews to join him for a crossing. This year it was finally my turn, and I will admit I was less than thrilled. Four hours each way on a boat, I thought, staring at grey water, when my cousins had come back raving about dolphins as if they had visited a theme park. I assumed they had exaggerated to wind me up. Dan met me at the harbour at six in the morning, handed me a pair of binoculars that looked older than I was, and told me the first rule of wildlife watching: the sea rewards patience, not enthusiasm. For the first hour I understood exactly what he meant. There was nothing but gulls, a distant fishing boat, and a cold wind that went straight through my supposedly waterproof jacket. I was beginning to compose a sarcastic message to my cousins when Dan touched my arm and pointed, without a word, towards a patch of water that looked no different from any other. Then the surface broke, and a fin curved out of the sea, followed by another, and another. A pod of common dolphins had decided our bow wave was the best game in town. They stayed with us for twenty minutes, weaving under the hull and leaping clear of the water, and I found myself shouting like a small child. Dan just smiled and said they turned up on roughly one crossing in three, so I should consider myself lucky. What he really wanted to show me, though, came later. Halfway across, the ferry slowed noticeably, and a voice on the loudspeaker asked passengers to keep to the starboard side. Dan explained that the captain had spotted a minke whale ahead and that company policy was to reduce speed and alter course rather than push through. Some tourists grumbled about the delay, and one man complained loudly that he had a connection to catch. Dan's expression hardened in a way I had never seen before. \"We're guests out here,\" he said quietly. \"The whale was using this water long before anyone printed a timetable.\" The whale itself was almost an anticlimax: a dark back, a small curved fin, a blow of misty breath, gone in seconds. Yet the hush that fell over the deck was extraordinary. Even the man with the connection lowered his phone and simply watched. On the return journey, Dan showed me the recording sheets the crew fill in for a marine research charity, noting every sighting with time, position and weather. He has submitted thousands of entries over the years, and researchers have used the ferry's data to track how warming seas are shifting the animals further north. It struck me that my uncle, who left school at sixteen and would never call himself a scientist, has probably contributed more to marine biology than most people with degrees. I came home sunburnt on one side of my face and unable to stop talking about fins and blows and bow waves. My cousins listened with knowing smiles. They had not exaggerated at all; if anything, they had undersold it.",
